# Week 4
# 1. use of an adjective with the ligature, "a":
Source: a:354
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nadaras  a   nagsubliak
na-daras a   n-ag-subli=ak
ADJ-fast LIG PF-I-return=ABS.1SG
`I returned quickly`

# Week 4
# 2. use of an adjective or verb. connected to the predicate 
# as a prepositional phase with the oblique noun marker iti,
# similar to a prepositional phrase:
Source: a:354
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Naglaylayak      iti    napaut
n-ag-sangit=ak   iti    na-paut
PF-I-cry=ABS.1SG OBL.SG ADJ-lasting
`I cried for a long time'

# Week 4
Source: a:35
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagpanunotka       iti     nauneg
n-ag-panunot=ka    iti     na-uneg
PF-I-think=ABS.2SG CORE.SG ADJ-deep
`You thought deeply`

# Week 4
Source: a:36
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagsaoda           iti    nalapat
n-ag-sao=da        iti    na-lapat
PF-I-speak=ABS.3PL OBL.SG ADJ-frank
`They spoke frankly`

# Week 4
# 3. use of a transitive verb denoting an adverbial notion
Source: a:354
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Igaedna            ti      agadal
i-gaed=na          ti      ag-adal
T-diligent=ERG.3SG CORE.SG I-study
`He studied diligently`

# Week 4
# 4. use of an adverb-like lexeme that does a require the ligature
# (ng)a when linking to a constituent- These words form a closed
# class and may aiso function as adjectives
Source: a:355
Vetted: s
Judgment: g
Phenomena: {adverbs}
Nagistayan ginetteb        ti      alingo    ti      tengngedna
Nagistayan getteb-{in}     ti      alingo    ti      tengnged=na
almost     tear.off-{PF.T} CORE.SG wild.boar CORE.SG neck=ERG.3SG
`The wild boar almost cut his neck`


